Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/belongsTo
Object: Relates a paper series to the session that series belongs to. A paper series may belong to one session, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperType
Object: The type of a paper, for example: a bill, a statutory instrument, a petition, a written statement or a set of annual accounts.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/
Object: A model describing parliamentary papers, their types and their presence in bundles and series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/inSeries
Object: Relates the existence of a parliamentary paper in a series to the series it forms part of. A paper series item forms part of one paper series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/positionsParliamentaryPaper
Object: Relates the existence of a parliamentary paper in a series to that parliamentary paper. A paper series item refers to one parliamentary paper.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/hasType
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to its type. A parliamentary paper may have one or more types.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperTypeParent
Object: Relates a paper type to its parent paper type. A paper type may have one or more parent paper types, or none.  A paper type may have one or more child paper types, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperSeriesItem
Object: A parliamentary paper as it exists as part of a paper series. A parliamentary paper forming part of a series may result in the paper being 'numbered' as part of that series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/ParliamentaryPaperWork
Object: A parliamentary paper made available to Parliament as realised in an expression made available to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperSeries
Object: A series of parliamentary papers, for example: the Treaty Series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperSeriesPrefix
Object: Relates a paper series to the prefix forming part of the 'number' of a parliamentary paper being part of that series.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/expressionOf
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the work the paper is an expression of. A parliamentary paper is an expression of one work. A parliamentary paper work may be expressed by one or more parliamentary papers.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/confersPrivilege
Object: Used to record if membership of a series confers parliamentary privilige.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperSeriesParent
Object: Relates a paper series to its parent paper series. A paper series may have one parent paper series, or none. A paper series may have one or more child paper series, or none. For example: the Treaty Series of in force treaties forms part of the overarching series grouping all treaties.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/paperSeriesFollows
Object: Relates a paper series to its predecessor series. A paper series may follow one series, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/formsPartOf
Object: Relates a parliamentary paper to the paper bundle it forms part of. A parliamentary paper may belong to one or more paper bundles, or none.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/ParliamentaryPaper
Object: The expression of a parliamentary paper work as made available to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/parliamentary-paper/PaperBundle
Object: A bundle of related parliamentary papers, for example: a bundle containing a statutory instrument paper and its related explanatory memorandum.
